<paragraph blockId="9.[546,1041,1205,1274]" box="[728,859,1248,1274]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<figureCitation box="[728,859,1248,1274]" captionStart-0="Fig" captionStart-1="Fig" captionStart-2="Fig" captionStart-3="Fig" captionStart-4="Fig" captionStartId-0="52.[189,232,1930,1956]" captionStartId-1="53.[189,232,1930,1956]" captionStartId-2="54.[189,232,1824,1850]" captionStartId-3="55.[188,231,1930,1956]" captionStartId-4="56.[189,232,1894,1920]" captionTargetBox-0="[190,1397,345,1886]" captionTargetBox-1="[193,1396,338,1884]" captionTargetBox-2="[210,1379,273,1783]" captionTargetBox-3="[191,1396,527,1887]" captionTargetBox-4="[192,1396,449,1849]" captionTargetId-0="figure@52.[187,1399,342,1888]" captionTargetId-1="figure@53.[190,1398,335,1887]" captionTargetId-2="figure@54.[207,1381,270,1785]" captionTargetId-3="figure@55.[188,1399,524,1890]" captionTargetId-4="figure@56.[189,1399,446,1852]" captionTargetPageId-0="52" captionTargetPageId-1="53" captionTargetPageId-2="54" captionTargetPageId-3="55" captionTargetPageId-4="56" captionText-0="Fig. 10. Adelges (Adelges) tardus (Dreyfus, 1888). Galls on Picea abies. A–B. Almost full-grown. C. Almost mature. D–E. Mature, first gallicolae have emerged. F–G. Fully opened galls. Scale bars: 10 mm." captionText-1="Fig. 11. Adelges (Adelges) tardus (Dreyfus, 1888) on Picea abies. A. Mature, opened gall with alate gallicolae on surface. B–I. Gallicolae laying eggs on needles in vicinity of their mother gall. J–K. Gallicolae in vitro. Scale bars for E–K: 1 mm." captionText-2="Fig. 12. Adelges (Adelges) tardus (Dreyfus, 1888). A–F. Hibernating pseudofundatrix nymphs on buds of Picea abies. Note the sparse, long, more or less straight wax filaments (most of them worn off, except in D–E). Often together with nymphs of A. (Sacciphantes) abietis (Linnaeus, 1758), whose wax filaments are dense, flattened and strongly curled (the specimen to the right in B). The nymphs usually hibernate on the surface of the bud, whereas those of A. abietis prefer bud bases and axils. G. Hibernating nymphs, which are easiest to find in the vicinity of the previous summer’s galls." captionText-3="Fig. 13. A–C. Adelges (Adelges) tardus (Dreyfus, 1888). Wax-covered pseudofundatrices at bases of developing galls on Picea abies. D. As A–C, but with the wax wool brushed off to expose the pseudofundatrix and her eggs." captionText-4="Fig. 14. A–B. Developing galls of Adelges (Adelges) tardus (Dreyfus, 1888) on Picea abies, close to galls of A. (Sacciphantes) abietis (Linnaeus, 1758). C. Half-grown galls of A. tardus and A. abietis on the same twig. Note the tufts of protruding needles on the A. tardus galls, apparently due to interference from A. abietis. Scale bars: 10 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834369" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834371" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834373" figureDoi-3="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834375" figureDoi-4="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3834377" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3834369/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3834371/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/3834373/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/3834375/files/figure.png" httpUri-4="https://zenodo.org/record/3834377/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs 10–14</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
